I was a “digital nomad” for 7 years, and thought I was a travel pro. Then we had kids and I realised I was playing on easy mode all along 🤦‍♂️

So we levelled up! Here are our best tricks for balancing work and travel with a family, from weekend breaks to multi-month stays:

1. "Speedy Everything"

Fast-track security, speedy boarding - if it gets you through faster, it's worth every penny. Then we book a lounge (through Priority Pass or some other scheme) to load up on snacks while waiting.

2. Get an extra seat

When we had a baby, we always bought an extra seat even though kids under 2 fly free on your lap. Having more space to spread out was totally worth it.

Having more space to spread out was totally worth it.

3. Home sweet home (exchange)

Airbnbs or home exchanges that are already set up for kids are gold. We're currently staying somewhere where they have kids the same age as ours, so it’s kitted out perfectly with age-appropriate toys.

4. Pre-order groceries

We book a grocery order to arrive when we do – or ideally beforehand if someone is available to take delivery. Avoiding that dreaded first "big shop" in a new place and arriving to a fully stocked fridge is a game-changer.

5. Get toys on order

If the place we’re staying doesn’t have toys already, we save lugging stuff around by getting them delivered in advance to a local shop or Amazon locker.

New toys = novelty = quiet (OK, not quiet – “occupied”) kids. We then leave them for the next people or donate them through a local group.

6. Bring in the babysitters

For trips longer than a week, we get a babysitter for every afternoon (through a local agency or app). That way we can get work done in the afternoon, and do family activities (or split the childcare between us) in the mornings.

Does this all add to the cost? Yes. Do I enjoy travel days now? Absolutely not. But this dulls some of the pain points, and lets us get into the groove of working and having a good time as quickly as possible.

I can summarise the path to financial freedom in just two words. And no, it's not 'work harder'.

Those words are: "own assets". But there's more to this than just traditional investing…

It's obvious that without owning assets, you can't get beyond "swapping time for money". You can make great money this way, but the cash stops whenever you do.

When you own assets, they can produce income and increase in value without any input from you.

But here's the bit most people miss: you don't have to BUY assets… you can create them too.

I own physical and financial assets like properties, shares, and gold.

I own physical and financial assets like properties, shares, and gold. But my most valuable assets cost me nothing:

• My books (I still get paid today for a book I wrote in 2014)
• My business (which we're all creating together, so everyone owns a piece)
• My mailing list (8,500 people who trust me – an asset potentially worth more than everything else combined)

Assets you create (rather than assets you buy) are far more valuable than people tend to realise.

Consider this:

Royalties from book making £1,000 per month = A financial asset worth £240,000 (at 5% annual return)

And it's a virtuous cycle: create an asset (like a book or online course); it generates income; invest that income in financial assets; they generate more income; reinvest in creating new assets... and the cycle continues.

Asset ownership is the lens I look at the world through. It guides my choices about where I spend my time and energy. It's not just about what I own now, but what I can create for the future.

Asset ownership isn't just for the wealthy—it's how you become wealthy.

For two years, I was obsessed with trying to strike gold – and frustrated by mostly failing. Finally, I got back to the mindset that’s grown our podcast over a decade: we do the best we can each week, and whatever happens happens.
It’s the viral hits that grow the channel – but they’re built on a foundation of regular uploads.

After 11 years, our podcast needed a refresh. Here are 5 key changes that breathed new life into our show:

1: Cut the fluff

We were ambling into episodes with a load of announcements and throat-clearing. Not great for hooking listeners.

Our challenge: hit the main content within 60 seconds. Result? The last two episodes I checked clocked in at 58 seconds. It launches listeners into the show with real momentum.

2: Beef up the length

Over time, some episodes had dipped to less than 15 minutes.
As a podcast listener, I often skip short episodes: too short for a commute, too brief to promise real value.

Our new rule: 20 minutes, minimum. It forces us to dig deeper and offer more substance.

Our new rule: 20 minutes, minimum. It forces us to dig deeper and offer more substance.

Adding length also comes from being more conversational. No more rattling off "5 things you need to know about [X]" lists – those belong elsewhere. Speaking of which…

3: Inject personality

People love podcasts for that "hanging out with friends" vibe. So we ditched "presenter mode”: we’re not podcast hosts, we’re your friends having a chat while you listen in.

Now we interject with silly comments, cut each other off, make noises of agreement… everything that happens in a normal conversation.

Sometimes (OK, often) it doesn’t work and our producer has to rescue it in the edit – but when it works, the show comes alive.

4: Cut the ads

We experimented with 30-second mid-roll ads for our services. The result? Crickets. No uptick in enquiries at all.

So we axed them. Now we stick to casual, contextual mentions. Just as effective, way less intrusive.

5: Make the listener the hero

"Community" might be a buzzword, but it matters. We now end each episode with a quick shout-out to a listener who's achieved something impressive. It reminds everyone they're part of something bigger.

The impact? It's tough to measure in downloads, but as podcast junkies ourselves, we hear the difference. It's objectively a better show.

Classic book 'The Millionaire Next Door' has sold more than 3 million copies – yet it preaches the exact opposite of what the rich actually do.

It says:

“Wealthy individuals are often conservative in their investment approach. They avoid speculative, high-risk investments and focus on preserving their capital through diversification”

In reality, the wealthiest:
• Go all-in on a single business
• Use leverage to increase returns
• Bet on lumpy, illiquid investments like real estate projects

Ask someone stepping off a yacht how they did it, and there’s one response I can guarantee they won’t give: “I bought a diversified collection of index funds and waited”.

So, why the disconnect? It's about how rich you want to be, and when.

The “capital-R Rich” path involves focus, effort and risk. You could end up mooring next to Bezos in a matter of years, or you might go back to square one.

Personal finance books mostly steer you away from aiming big, because it’s risky and hard to give templated advice about.

Compound interest is supposedly the “8th wonder of the world”, but if you’re relying on it to make you financially free, prepare for disappointment.

The classic example is that Warren Buffet made 90% of his wealth after he turned 60. Not because he suddenly got smarter – but because the first 40 years of compounding started to kick in.

Yet, for me, this is precisely the problem… it takes DECADES to see any benefit.

Here’s an example:

• Start aged 20, £30,000 salary, invest 10% of it
• Earn 5% more every year
• Investments make a 5% return every year

After 40 years – when you turn 60 –  you’d have £844,000.

And incredibly, your investments are now growing by £40,000 every year.

Amazing! But…

What’s the situation at the halfway point, 20 years in? Would you be halfway there? 

Far from it.

You’d only have £161,000 – of which two-thirds is money you contributed rather than investment returns. And your investments would only be growing by £7,484 per year.

That’s after two decades! If you run the numbers, it takes around 30 years to really notice the benefits of compounding.

This isn’t an argument against saving and investing.

Eventually, it’ll come good. And if you live as long as Buffet, it’ll leave you in an incredible position.
